By Lizzy Okoji Gov. Yahaya Bello of Kogi on Saturday in Lokoja joined other leaders in paying respect to heroes of the armed forces who lost their lives in service. Bello commemorated the day by laying a wreath in honour of the fallen heroes at the World War I and II Cenotaph in Lokoja. Addressing journalists at the event, Bello reiterated his administration’s commitment and support to the servicemen and families of the fallen heroes. “The labour of the fallen heroes who paid the ultimate price to keep the country together shall never be in vain. “And the only way to ensure that is for the government at all levels to rise up in ensuring a peaceful society,” Bello said. Bello said that his administration would continue to prioritise security of all citizens and residents of the state, noting that the welfare and logistic support to servicemen in the state remained paramount. Responding to questions on calls to join the 2023 presidential race, Bello said that he had been aware of similar calls from “very part of the country including youths, women organisations and associations. “I will respond to the calls loud and clear at the appropriate time”. Bello commended Malam Mai Mala Buni, Caretaker Extraordinary Convention Committee Chairman of the All Progressives Congress (APC) for repositioning the party, noting the efforts geared towards the forthcoming convention of the party. He noted that the APC under the leadership of Mai Mala “is more formidable in strength and membership”.(NAN)